        <div class="text-container">

            <h2>The Pizza Industry in Detroit</h2>

            <p>
                Detroit-style pizza has developed a strong regional identity, but major franchises like Little Caesars and Domino’s often overshadow it. In 1944, following World War II, Gus Guerra, an Italian immigrant, became a partner at Buddy’s Rendezvous. In 1946, Gus invented Detroit-style pizza by using bread pans and his mother-in-law’s pizza recipe to create the now-famous Detroit pan pizza.

                Buddy’s Pizza went on to become a key reference point in Detroit’s pizza scene, often serving as the standard other pizzerias were compared to.
            </p>

            <p>
                As pizza grew in popularity across the United States, regional pizza identities began to decline under the pressure of franchise expansion, mass production, standardization, and efficiency.

                One of the most recognizable pizza chains in the world, Domino’s (originally Dominick’s) in Michigan, opened in 1960. Domino’s gained popularity not primarily for its taste but for its reliability. Another major franchise that emerged from Michigan was Little Caesars, founded by Mike Ilitch in 1959. Between 1961 and 1992, it expanded from 2 to 4,000 outlets.
            </p>

            <p>
                Although Detroit still maintains an identity through Buddy’s Pizza, which continues today, pizza franchises in the United States have increasingly shifted toward standardized, mass-produced products rather than distinct regional identities.

                Even though Detroit still has its Detroit-style pizza, the quality has been debated. In 1953, Gus sold Buddy’s, which has since had four owners or investors. As a result, current owners who recently took over Buddy’s have stated that customers have raised concerns about quality. They also explained that the pizza has struggled to expand beyond central Detroit and that the recipe has changed over time.

                As a result, pizza in Detroit has struggled to maintain its signature style and identity, which increasingly overlaps with those of large chains like Little Caesars and Domino’s. In contrast, Windsor pizzerias have adapted to changing markets while maintaining their identity and continuing to grow their customer base.
            </p>

        </div>

